window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["anatomy-physiology"]={"slug": "anatomy-physiology", "title": "Cardiovascular Anatomy & Physiology", "tagline": "From chamber pressures and coronary territories to pressure-volume loops, wall stress, and the bedside signs and drugs they explain.", "level": 1, "readMin": 34, "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module rebuilds cardiac anatomy and physiology from the ground up, but pitches every concept at the level a cardiology fellow is expected to <em>reason from</em> rather than merely recite. The organizing principle is that structure predicts pressure, pressure predicts flow, and flow predicts the physical exam and the drug you reach for."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Map the four chambers, four valves, and three major coronary arteries onto their perfusion territories and predict which wall fails when a given vessel occludes.", "Reconstruct the cardiac cycle as a sequence of pressure crossovers, and explain why each valve event generates a specific heart sound.", "Translate the cardiac cycle into a pressure-volume loop and read stroke volume, ejection fraction, contractility, and afterload directly off the loop.", "Define the four determinants of cardiac output quantitatively and apply Frank-Starling and Laplace's law to bedside decisions.", "Distinguish systemic from pulmonary circulation by numeric pressures and explain why the right and left ventricles are architecturally different.", "Derive the determinants of myocardial oxygen supply and demand and anchor each anti-ischemic and heart-failure drug to the lever it pulls.", "Connect physiology to the JVP waveform and the splitting of S2 so that the exam becomes a readout of intracardiac events."]}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why it matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Almost every downstream cardiology decision is a physiology problem wearing clinical clothing. Whether to give fluids or diurese, why a murmur radiates where it does, which coronary to open first, why a patient with a normal ejection fraction is still in florid heart failure: each collapses back to preload, afterload, contractility, wall stress, and oxygen balance. Fellows who carry these primitives can reconstruct an unfamiliar disease at the bedside; those who memorize disease-by-disease eventually run out of memory."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "A useful habit: for every patient, silently state their approximate LV filling pressure, systemic vascular resistance, and cardiac output. If you cannot, you do not yet understand their hemodynamics, only their diagnosis."}]}, {"id": "essential-physiology", "title": "Essential physiology: the pressures that run the heart", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The heart is two pumps in series feeding two circulations with very different resistances. The left ventricle generates roughly five times the pressure of the right because the systemic bed it drives has roughly five times the resistance of the pulmonary bed. Committing the normal chamber pressures to memory is the single highest-yield act in cardiac physiology, because nearly every hemodynamic diagnosis is a deviation from these numbers."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/wiggers.svg", "alt": "Wiggers diagram", "caption": "The Wiggers diagram linking pressures, volumes, ECG, and heart sounds across the cardiac cycle.", "credit": "DanielChangMD & xavax — CC BY-SA 2.5, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Wiggers_Diagram.svg"}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Normal resting chamber and vessel pressures (mmHg). Memorize these as anchors.", "head": ["Site", "Pressure (mmHg)", "Note"], "rows": [["Right atrium (mean)", "2 to 6", "Approximates CVP and RV preload"], ["Right ventricle", "25 / 4", "Systolic / end-diastolic"], ["Pulmonary artery", "25 / 10 (mean ~14)", "Mean PA >20 defines pulmonary hypertension"], ["Pulmonary capillary wedge", "6 to 12", "Surrogate for LA and LV filling pressure"], ["Left atrium (mean)", "8 to 12", "Rises first in left heart failure"], ["Left ventricle", "120 / 8", "Systolic / end-diastolic (LVEDP)"], ["Aorta", "120 / 80 (mean ~93)", "Diastolic pressure drives coronary flow"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic: for the normal right-heart pressures walking outward from the RA, remember the rising staircase \"2, 25, 25, 10\" (RA mean ~2 to 6, RV systolic 25, PA systolic 25, PA diastolic ~10). The RV and PA share the same systolic peak because the open pulmonic valve makes them a common chamber in systole; a systolic gradient between them means pulmonic stenosis."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Cardiac output (CO)", "def": "Stroke volume times heart rate; normal 4 to 8 L/min. The quantity the entire system exists to regulate."}, {"term": "Cardiac index (CI)", "def": "CO divided by body surface area; normal 2.5 to 4.0 L/min/m2. Below ~2.2 defines cardiogenic shock."}, {"term": "Stroke volume (SV)", "def": "End-diastolic volume minus end-systolic volume; roughly 70 mL (120 mL EDV, 50 mL ESV)."}, {"term": "Ejection fraction (EF)", "def": "SV/EDV, normally 55 to 70 percent. A ratio, not a flow: it can mislead when EDV is very large or small."}]}]}, {"id": "chambers-and-valves", "title": "Chambers, valves, and the fibrous skeleton", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Blood returns from the body to the right atrium via the superior and inferior venae cavae, crosses the tricuspid valve into the right ventricle, is ejected through the pulmonic valve into the lungs, returns oxygenated to the left atrium via four pulmonary veins, crosses the mitral valve into the left ventricle, and is ejected through the aortic valve to the body. The two atrioventricular valves (tricuspid, mitral) close at the start of systole; the two semilunar valves (aortic, pulmonic) close at the start of diastole."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Tricuspid valve", "def": "Three leaflets; right AV valve. Regurgitation produces a large v wave in the JVP and a pulsatile liver."}, {"term": "Mitral valve", "def": "Two leaflets (anterior, posterior) tethered by chordae to two papillary muscles. The anterolateral papillary muscle has dual blood supply (LAD diagonal and LCx marginal); the posteromedial has a single supply (usually the PDA) and is the one that ruptures in inferior MI."}, {"term": "Aortic valve", "def": "Three cusps (right, left, non-coronary). The right and left coronary ostia arise from the corresponding sinuses of Valsalva."}, {"term": "Pulmonic valve", "def": "Three cusps; lowest-pressure valve, hence the last to be affected by most acquired disease."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the aortic cusps and coronary origins: the <strong>R</strong>ight coronary comes off the <strong>R</strong>ight cusp, the <strong>L</strong>eft coronary off the <strong>L</strong>eft cusp, and the <strong>N</strong>on-coronary cusp gives off <strong>N</strong>one. The non-coronary cusp sits adjacent to the interatrial septum, which is why aortic-root pathology there can involve the AV node."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The four valves are anchored to the <strong>cardiac fibrous skeleton</strong>, a ring of dense connective tissue that electrically insulates the atria from the ventricles. This insulation is why the AV node and His bundle are the sole normal electrical conduit between them, and why an accessory pathway that bridges this skeleton produces pre-excitation.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The left ventricle is a prolate ellipsoid built for pressure; the right ventricle is a crescent wrapped around it, built for volume. This geometry is why the RV tolerates chronic volume load well but fails abruptly against acute afterload, as in acute pulmonary embolism.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Labeled figures of the four cardiac chambers, valve leaflets, papillary muscle anatomy, and the fibrous skeleton. On the landing page, search \"cardiac chambers\" or \"heart valves\" for annotated CT, MRI, and illustrated cross-sections that show leaflet orientation and the anterolateral versus posteromedial papillary muscles.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac chambers and valve anatomy"}]}, {"id": "coronary-anatomy", "title": "Coronary anatomy, territories, and dominance", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Two coronary arteries arise from the aortic root. The left main divides into the left anterior descending (LAD) and the left circumflex (LCx); the right coronary artery (RCA) arises separately. Knowing which wall each vessel feeds lets you read the culprit lesion off a 12-lead ECG before angiography."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/coronary-arteries.svg", "alt": "Coronary artery anatomy", "caption": "Coronary arteries and their perfusion territories.", "credit": "Patrick J. Lynch, Fred the Oyster & Mikael Häggström — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coronary_arteries.svg"}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Coronary territories and ECG correlates.", "head": ["Artery", "Myocardium supplied", "ECG leads"], "rows": [["LAD", "Anterior wall, anterior 2/3 of septum, LV apex", "V1 to V4 (anteroseptal)"], ["LCx", "Lateral and posterolateral LV wall", "I, aVL, V5 to V6 (lateral)"], ["RCA", "Inferior wall, RV, SA node (~60%), AV node (~90%)", "II, III, aVF (inferior)"], ["PDA (dominance vessel)", "Inferior septum and inferior wall; gives AV-nodal branch in right dominance", "Determines inferior/posterior supply"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the inferior culprit: \"the RCA runs the <strong>rhythm</strong>\". The RCA supplies the SA node in ~60 percent and the AV node in ~90 percent, so inferior MI classically brings bradycardia and AV block. Pair it with \"<strong>LAD = widow-maker</strong>\" for the anterior wall and septum, and \"<strong>Circ = lateral</strong>\" (I, aVL, V5 to V6)."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Coronary dominance", "def": "Defined by which artery gives rise to the posterior descending artery (PDA). Right-dominant in roughly 85 percent, left-dominant in about 7 to 10 percent, codominant in the remainder."}, {"term": "Diagonal branches", "def": "LAD branches to the anterolateral wall."}, {"term": "Obtuse marginal branches", "def": "LCx branches to the lateral wall."}, {"term": "Acute marginal branches", "def": "RCA branches supplying the RV free wall."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Inferior MI (II, III, aVF) is RCA in ~85 percent, and the RCA supplies the AV node and often the RV. Get a right-sided ECG (V4R): RV infarction makes the patient preload-dependent, so nitrates and aggressive diuresis can precipitate profound hypotension."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Coronary flow is unique in that the left coronary bed is perfused almost entirely in diastole: during systole, intramyocardial pressure exceeds coronary driving pressure and squeezes the subendocardium. This is why tachycardia (shortening diastole) and aortic stenosis (raising systolic wall stress while lowering aortic diastolic pressure) both threaten the subendocardium first.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Because resting extraction is already near-maximal, the myocardium meets rising demand by vasodilating the microcirculation and increasing flow. The ratio of maximal hyperemic to resting flow is coronary flow reserve; an epicardial stenosis, microvascular dysfunction, or LV hypertrophy each erodes it, which is the physiologic substrate behind fractional flow reserve and stress-test perfusion defects.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Annotated coronary angiographic and CT-angiography figures showing the LAD, LCx, RCA, PDA, and the standard perfusion-territory diagrams (17-segment bullseye). Search \"coronary artery anatomy\" or \"coronary territories\" on the landing page for labeled cath-view and cross-sectional images.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: coronary artery anatomy and territories"}]}, {"id": "conduction-system", "title": "The conduction system", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Electrical activation follows a fixed anatomic highway with deliberate speed changes. The sinoatrial node sets the rhythm; the atrioventricular node imposes a delay that separates atrial from ventricular contraction; the His-Purkinje system then distributes the impulse to the ventricles almost simultaneously."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/conduction-system.svg", "alt": "Cardiac conduction system", "caption": "The cardiac conduction system: SA node, AV node, His-Purkinje.", "credit": "Madhero88 — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Electrical_conduction_system_of_the_heart.svg"}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["SA node (high right atrium, RCA-supplied in ~60%): intrinsic rate 60 to 100 bpm, the dominant pacemaker.", "Internodal and interatrial spread depolarizes the atria, producing the P wave and atrial contraction.", "AV node (floor of the right atrium in the triangle of Koch, AV-nodal branch usually from RCA): slow conduction (~0.05 m/s) creates the physiologic delay, seen as the PR segment, allowing atrial kick to complete before ventricular systole.", "Bundle of His and left/right bundle branches carry the impulse into the septum.", "Purkinje fibers conduct fastest in the heart (2 to 4 m/s), depolarizing both ventricles nearly simultaneously to produce a narrow QRS and a coordinated squeeze."]}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Intrinsic pacemaker rates (the escape hierarchy).", "head": ["Structure", "Intrinsic rate", "Clinical relevance"], "rows": [["SA node", "60 to 100 bpm", "Normal pacemaker"], ["AV junction", "40 to 60 bpm", "Junctional escape if SA fails"], ["His-Purkinje / ventricle", "20 to 40 bpm", "Ventricular escape in complete heart block; unreliable"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the escape hierarchy: count down by 20s from 60 to zero and pair with the anatomy: <strong>60-100 SA, 40-60 junction, 20-40 ventricle</strong>. The lower and slower the pacemaker, the wider and less reliable the escape rhythm, which is why an unstable complete heart block with a 30-bpm wide escape needs pacing, not just atropine."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The AV nodal delay is not a design flaw; it is the atrial kick's protected window. Losing it (as in atrial fibrillation or high-grade block with AV dissociation) can drop cardiac output by 20 to 30 percent in a stiff, preload-dependent ventricle."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "AV nodal conduction depends on slow calcium-channel action potentials and is heavily vagally innervated, which is why adenosine, beta-blockers, and non-dihydropyridine calcium blockers work there. His-Purkinje tissue uses fast sodium channels and is largely vagally denervated, explaining why atropine helps nodal but not infranodal block.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Labeled illustrations of the SA node, internodal tracts, AV node in the triangle of Koch, bundle of His, and the left and right bundle branches with Purkinje network. Search \"cardiac conduction system\" on the landing page for annotated anatomic diagrams.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac conduction system"}]}, {"id": "systemic-vs-pulmonary-circulation", "title": "Systemic versus pulmonary circulation", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The two circulations carry the same output but at radically different pressures because resistance differs. Pulmonary vascular resistance is roughly one-tenth of systemic vascular resistance, so the right ventricle achieves the same flow at a fraction of the pressure. This asymmetry explains the ventricles' differing wall thicknesses and their differing responses to disease."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Comparing the two circulations.", "head": ["Property", "Systemic (left heart)", "Pulmonary (right heart)"], "rows": [["Driving pump", "Left ventricle", "Right ventricle"], ["Mean pressure", "~93 mmHg (aorta)", "~14 mmHg (PA)"], ["Vascular resistance", "SVR ~800 to 1200 dyn s cm-5", "PVR ~40 to 150 dyn s cm-5"], ["Wall thickness", "~10 mm (pressure chamber)", "~3 to 5 mm (volume chamber)"], ["Response to load", "Concentric hypertrophy to pressure", "Dilates to volume; fails against acute pressure"]]}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Resistance (simplified Ohm)", "def": "Resistance = (pressure in minus pressure out) / flow. For the systemic bed, SVR = 80 x (MAP minus RA pressure) / CO."}, {"term": "Transpulmonary gradient", "def": "Mean PA pressure minus wedge pressure; separates pulmonary vascular disease from passive congestion from the left heart."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "A thin-walled RV cannot acutely generate more than ~40 to 50 mmHg systolic. A previously normal RV facing a sudden large pulmonary embolism dilates, becomes ischemic, and fails; a chronically pressure-loaded RV (long-standing pulmonary hypertension) hypertrophies and can generate suprasystemic pressures. Same organ, opposite tolerances, depending on time course."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The current hemodynamic definition of pulmonary hypertension is a mean PA pressure above 20 mmHg at rest. A wedge at or below 15 mmHg with a pulmonary vascular resistance above 2 Wood units marks precapillary (pulmonary vascular) disease; a wedge above 15 mmHg marks postcapillary disease driven by the left heart. The wedge and PVR are what separate a pulmonary problem from upstream left-heart plumbing.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "cardiac-cycle", "title": "The cardiac cycle and the heart sounds", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The cardiac cycle is best understood as a sequence of pressure crossovers that open and close valves. Every heart sound is a valve event, and every valve event is a moment where two chamber pressures cross. The Wiggers diagram stacks aortic, LV, and LA pressure tracings against the ECG, the phonocardiogram, and the ventricular volume curve so all of these line up in time."}, {"type": "steps", "items": ["Atrial contraction: the a wave adds final preload (atrial kick), producing the S4 if the ventricle is stiff.", "Isovolumic contraction: LV pressure exceeds LA pressure, mitral valve closes (S1); all valves shut, volume fixed, pressure climbs steeply.", "Ejection: LV pressure exceeds aortic pressure, aortic valve opens; stroke volume leaves, LV volume falls from EDV to ESV.", "Isovolumic relaxation: LV pressure falls below aortic pressure, aortic valve closes (S2); again all valves shut, volume fixed, pressure falls.", "Filling: LV pressure falls below LA pressure, mitral valve opens; rapid early filling (the moment of a pathologic S3), then diastasis, then atrial kick, and the cycle repeats."]}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Heart sounds and their cycle events.", "head": ["Sound", "Event", "Meaning"], "rows": [["S1", "Mitral + tricuspid closure", "Onset of systole (isovolumic contraction)"], ["S2", "Aortic (A2) + pulmonic (P2) closure", "Onset of diastole (isovolumic relaxation)"], ["S3", "End of rapid early filling", "Normal in youth; pathologic = volume overload / failing ventricle"], ["S4", "Atrial kick into stiff ventricle", "Pathologic = reduced compliance (HTN, ischemia, HFpEF)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "S3 is the sound of a compliant, overfilled ventricle being suddenly stretched; S4 is the sound of a stiff ventricle being pushed against by the atrium. Memorably: S3 = floppy and full, S4 = stiff and struggling. An S4 cannot exist in atrial fibrillation because it requires organized atrial contraction."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for auscultation position and the valve areas: \"<strong>A</strong>ll <strong>P</strong>hysicians <strong>T</strong>ake <strong>M</strong>oney\" walks you top-down and right-to-left across the precordium: <strong>A</strong>ortic (right 2nd interspace), <strong>P</strong>ulmonic (left 2nd interspace), <strong>T</strong>ricuspid (left lower sternal border), <strong>M</strong>itral (apex). Right-sided sounds (tricuspid, pulmonic) get louder with inspiration; left-sided ones do not."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "The Wiggers diagram with aligned aortic, ventricular, and atrial pressure tracings, ventricular volume, ECG, and phonocardiogram, plus labeled valve-event timing. Search \"cardiac cycle\" or \"Wiggers diagram\" on the landing page for the classic annotated composite.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: cardiac cycle / Wiggers diagram"}]}, {"id": "pressure-volume-loops", "title": "Pressure-volume loops: the cycle in one diagram", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Plotting LV pressure (y) against LV volume (x) turns the cardiac cycle into a closed loop traversed counterclockwise. Its four sides are the four phases, and its corners mark the valve events. The loop is the single most powerful tool for reasoning about load and contractility because you can read the key variables straight off it."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/pv-loop.jpg", "alt": "Pressure-volume loop", "caption": "A left-ventricular pressure–volume loop.", "credit": "Andyhenton83 — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Cardiac_Pressure_Volume_Loop.jpg"}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Bottom-right corner", "def": "End-diastole: mitral closes, S1. Its x-coordinate is EDV; its pressure is LVEDP (preload)."}, {"term": "Right (upstroke) side", "def": "Isovolumic contraction: vertical line, no volume change."}, {"term": "Top side", "def": "Ejection: aortic valve open; volume falls left from EDV to ESV."}, {"term": "Top-left corner", "def": "End-systole: aortic closes, S2. Its coordinates lie on the ESPVR line."}, {"term": "Left (downstroke) side", "def": "Isovolumic relaxation: vertical line back down."}, {"term": "Width of the loop", "def": "EDV minus ESV = stroke volume. The loop's area is stroke work."}]}, {"type": "p", "text": "Two boundary lines frame every loop. The <strong>end-systolic pressure-volume relationship (ESPVR)</strong> is the line touched by the top-left corner across all loading conditions; its slope is <em>end-systolic elastance (Ees)</em>, a load-independent index of contractility. The <strong>end-diastolic pressure-volume relationship (EDPVR)</strong> is the curved lower boundary describing passive diastolic compliance.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Because Ees is load-independent, it is the closest bedside-conceptual analogue to true contractility. Ejection fraction, by contrast, is load-dependent: a patient can have a preserved EF with a depressed Ees if afterload is low, which is one reason EF underdiagnoses systolic dysfunction in mitral regurgitation.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Annotated left-ventricular pressure-volume loops labeling the four phases, the ESPVR and EDPVR boundary lines, stroke volume, stroke work, and the characteristic shifts with changing preload, afterload, and contractility. Search \"pressure-volume loop\" on the landing page.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia: pressure-volume loops"}]}, {"id": "determinants-of-cardiac-output", "title": "Determinants of cardiac output", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Cardiac output is heart rate times stroke volume, and stroke volume has exactly three levers: preload, afterload, and contractility. Every inotrope, vasodilator, diuretic, and rate-control drug acts on one of these four variables. Fluency here is the difference between managing a number and managing a patient."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Preload", "def": "End-diastolic sarcomere stretch, clinically indexed by EDV or LVEDP. Governed by venous return. More preload raises SV via the Frank-Starling mechanism."}, {"term": "Afterload", "def": "The load the ventricle ejects against, best expressed as systolic wall stress (a function of pressure and radius), approximated clinically by SVR and systolic pressure. More afterload lowers SV in a failing ventricle."}, {"term": "Contractility (inotropy)", "def": "The intrinsic force of contraction at a fixed load, indexed by Ees. Raised by sympathetic tone, catecholamines, digoxin; lowered by ischemia, acidosis, beta-blockade."}, {"term": "Heart rate", "def": "Multiplies stroke volume into output, but excessive rate shortens diastolic filling and coronary perfusion time, eventually lowering both SV and supply."}]}, {"type": "p", "text": "The <strong>Frank-Starling mechanism</strong> is the length-tension relationship of cardiac muscle: within physiologic limits, greater end-diastolic fiber length (preload) increases the force of the next contraction, because sarcomere stretch toward ~2.2 micrometers optimizes actin-myosin overlap and increases myofilament calcium sensitivity. This lets the two ventricles auto-match their outputs beat to beat without external control."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the stroke-volume levers: <strong>\"CO = HR x SV, and SV rides on PAC\"</strong> (<strong>P</strong>reload, <strong>A</strong>fterload, <strong>C</strong>ontractility). Every cardiovascular drug you will ever start is pulling exactly one of these four handles; naming the handle before you write the order prevents most hemodynamic mistakes."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The failing heart operates on a flattened, downshifted Starling curve: giving it more preload buys little extra stroke volume but a lot of pulmonary congestion. This is precisely why the treatment of decompensated systolic heart failure is usually to reduce preload and afterload, not to augment them."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "The normal ventricle is preload-sensitive and afterload-insensitive; the failing ventricle inverts this, becoming preload-insensitive and exquisitely afterload-sensitive. That single inversion explains why afterload reduction (ACE inhibitors, ARNI, hydralazine-nitrates) is disease-modifying in HFrEF but does little in a normal heart.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "laplace-wall-stress", "title": "Laplace's law and wall stress", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Wall stress is the true afterload the myofibers feel, and Laplace's law tells you how geometry sets it. For a thin-walled sphere, wall stress is proportional to pressure times radius divided by twice the wall thickness. Every term in that expression is a therapeutic or pathologic lever."}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Laplace relation", "def": "Wall stress is approximately (P x r) / (2h), where P is intraventricular pressure, r is chamber radius, and h is wall thickness."}, {"term": "Implication of pressure (P)", "def": "Hypertension and aortic stenosis raise wall stress by raising P; lowering blood pressure lowers myocardial oxygen demand."}, {"term": "Implication of radius (r)", "def": "A dilated ventricle has higher wall stress at the same pressure, a vicious cycle in heart failure; reducing chamber size (diuresis, reverse remodeling) lowers demand."}, {"term": "Implication of thickness (h)", "def": "Concentric hypertrophy is the heart's structural response to normalize wall stress against chronic pressure load, at the cost of increased mass and impaired relaxation."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the wall-stress equation: <strong>\"Pressure and Radius push it up, Thickness pulls it down\"</strong> (stress ~ P x r / 2h). Read left to right it also predicts the two hypertrophy patterns: chronic high <strong>P</strong> thickens the wall (concentric), chronic volume raises <strong>r</strong> and dilates it (eccentric)."}, {"type": "p", "text": "This single relation unifies several diseases. In chronic pressure overload (aortic stenosis, hypertension), the ventricle adds sarcomeres in parallel and thickens (h up) to hold wall stress constant, producing concentric hypertrophy. In chronic volume overload (aortic or mitral regurgitation), it adds sarcomeres in series and dilates (r up), producing eccentric hypertrophy. Laplace explains why a dilated, thin-walled failing heart is metabolically expensive: high r and low h both drive wall stress, hence oxygen demand, upward.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Laplace also explains the danger of afterload mismatch after mitral valve replacement in chronic MR. The regurgitant orifice had been a low-impedance popoff valve; abolishing it suddenly raises the pressure the (already dilated, high-radius) ventricle must eject against, unmasking latent systolic dysfunction. This is why the EF threshold for surgery in MR is set higher (~60 percent) than for other lesions.", "depth": 3}]}, {"id": "pv-loop-shifts-in-disease", "title": "Reading disease off the pressure-volume loop", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Once the loop is internalized, valvular and myocardial diseases become predictable deformations of it. Learn these four archetypes and most hemodynamics follows by interpolation."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Characteristic pressure-volume loop changes.", "head": ["Condition", "Loop change", "Mechanism"], "rows": [["Increased preload (volume)", "Loop widens to the right; SV rises", "Higher EDV recruits Frank-Starling reserve"], ["Increased afterload", "Loop taller and narrower; SV falls; ESV rises", "Ventricle ejects against higher pressure, stops sooner"], ["Increased contractility", "Top-left corner shifts up/left (steeper ESPVR); SV rises", "Greater force empties to a lower ESV"], ["Systolic HF (low contractility)", "Loop shifts right, flattens; ESV up, SV/EF down", "Depressed Ees, compensatory dilation"], ["Aortic stenosis", "Very tall loop; LV pressure far exceeds aortic during ejection", "Pressure-overload; gradient across valve"], ["Mitral regurgitation", "Loss of isovolumic contraction phase; loop opens on the left", "Ventricle unloads into the atrium before aortic opening"], ["Aortic regurgitation", "Loss of isovolumic relaxation phase; loop widens greatly", "Continued LV filling from aorta during diastole; huge SV"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "In pure mitral or aortic regurgitation the isovolumic phase on the corresponding side of the loop disappears, because a valve that should be closed is leaking. Spotting the missing vertical segment tells you which valve is incompetent before you read the echo."}]}, {"id": "oxygen-supply-demand", "title": "Myocardial oxygen supply and demand", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Ischemia is always a supply-demand mismatch, and each side of that equation is a short, fixed list. Because the myocardium already extracts roughly 70 to 75 percent of delivered oxygen at rest (the highest extraction of any organ), it cannot meet increased demand by extracting more; it must increase flow. Anything that limits coronary flow reserve therefore risks ischemia."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "The oxygen balance sheet.", "head": ["Supply (delivery)", "Demand (consumption, MVO2)"], "rows": [["Coronary blood flow (~250 mL/min, ~5% of CO)", "Heart rate"], ["Diastolic perfusion time (falls with tachycardia)", "Contractility (inotropic state)"], ["Coronary perfusion pressure = aortic diastolic minus LVEDP", "Wall stress (afterload x radius / thickness, by Laplace)"], ["Oxygen content (hemoglobin, SaO2)", ""]]}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Coronary perfusion pressure", "def": "Aortic diastolic pressure minus LV end-diastolic pressure. Hypotension, tachycardia, and elevated LVEDP each erode it, which is why they all worsen ischemia."}, {"term": "Subendocardial vulnerability", "def": "The subendocardium is perfused last and compressed most during systole, so it is the first layer to become ischemic and infarct."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for demand at the bedside: the <strong>rate-pressure (double) product</strong>, heart rate times systolic BP, tracks MVO2. Anything that raises both at once (pain, agitation, uncontrolled hypertension with tachycardia) drives demand ischemia, which is why heart-rate and blood-pressure control are the first two anti-ischemic maneuvers you reach for."}, {"type": "p", "text": "This framework rationalizes anti-ischemic therapy. Beta-blockers lower heart rate and contractility (demand down) and lengthen diastole (supply up). Nitrates reduce preload and thus wall stress (demand down) and dilate epicardial coronaries (supply up). This is also why aortic stenosis causes angina despite normal coronaries: it simultaneously raises demand (high systolic wall stress) and lowers supply (reduced aortic diastolic pressure and elevated LVEDP).", "depth": 2}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "The tachycardic, hypotensive patient is in a coronary double-jeopardy: shortened diastole cuts perfusion time while low aortic diastolic pressure cuts the driving gradient, and rising demand meets falling supply. Reflexively giving a chronotrope or a pure vasodilator here can convert demand ischemia into infarction."}]}, {"id": "pharmacology-anchored", "title": "Pharmacology anchored to physiology", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Because stroke volume has only three levers plus rate, the entire cardiovascular formulary sorts cleanly onto them. The two tables below are the ones worth carrying: anti-ischemic drugs that manipulate the oxygen balance sheet, and the four pillars of guideline-directed medical therapy for HFrEF that manipulate preload, afterload, and remodeling. Doses are standard adult starting and target doses; always retitrate to blood pressure, heart rate, renal function, and potassium."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Anti-ischemic / anti-anginal drugs mapped to the oxygen balance sheet.", "head": ["Drug (class)", "Mechanism / lever", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Major side effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Metoprolol succinate (beta-1 blocker)", "Lowers HR and contractility (demand down), lengthens diastole (supply up)", "25 to 50 mg PO daily", "Up to 200 mg daily, titrate to HR ~55 to 60", "Decompensated HF, high-grade AV block, marked bradycardia, cocaine chest pain", "Fatigue, bradycardia, bronchospasm, masked hypoglycemia", "HR, BP, signs of congestion"], ["Amlodipine (dihydropyridine CCB)", "Arterial/coronary vasodilation lowers afterload and epicardial spasm", "2.5 to 5 mg PO daily", "10 mg daily", "Severe hypotension; caution in severe aortic stenosis", "Peripheral edema, flushing, headache, reflex tachycardia", "BP, peripheral edema"], ["Diltiazem (non-dihydropyridine CCB)", "Lowers HR, AV conduction, and afterload", "120 to 180 mg ER daily", "Up to 360 mg daily", "HFrEF / LV systolic dysfunction, high-grade AV block; avoid routine combo with a beta-blocker", "Bradycardia, AV block, constipation, edema", "HR, BP, PR interval"], ["Isosorbide mononitrate (nitrate)", "Venodilation cuts preload and wall stress (demand down); dilates epicardial coronaries (supply up)", "30 mg PO daily", "30 to 120 mg daily with a 10 to 14 h nitrate-free interval", "PDE5 inhibitor within 24 to 48 h, RV infarction, severe AS or HOCM", "Headache, hypotension, tolerance", "BP; enforce nitrate-free interval"], ["Ranolazine (late I-Na inhibitor)", "Reduces late sodium current and diastolic wall tension without affecting HR or BP", "500 mg PO BID", "1000 mg PO BID", "Hepatic cirrhosis, concomitant strong CYP3A inhibitors or QT-prolonging drugs", "Dizziness, constipation, nausea, QT prolongation", "QTc, hepatic and renal function"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Ranolazine is the anti-anginal that does not lower heart rate or blood pressure, which makes it the go-to add-on for the patient with refractory angina who is already bradycardic or hypotensive on a beta-blocker and nitrate. It is anti-anginal, not prognosis-modifying, so it does not replace GDMT.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "table", "caption": "The four pillars of HFrEF guideline-directed medical therapy (ACC/AHA/HFSA). Start low, uptitrate every 1 to 2 weeks as tolerated.", "head": ["Drug (class)", "Mechanism / lever", "Start dose", "Target dose", "Key contraindication", "Major side effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Sacubitril/valsartan (ARNI)", "Neprilysin inhibition raises natriuretic peptides + ARB afterload reduction", "24/26 to 49/51 mg PO BID", "97/103 mg PO BID", "Prior angioedema, pregnancy, concomitant ACEi (need 36 h washout), eGFR <30 caution", "Hypotension, hyperkalemia, angioedema, renal dysfunction", "BP, K, creatinine at 1 to 2 weeks"], ["Carvedilol (beta-blocker)", "Lowers HR and contractility, reverses remodeling", "3.125 mg PO BID", "25 mg BID (50 mg BID if >85 kg)", "Decompensated HF, marked bradycardia, high-grade AV block", "Fatigue, bradycardia, early transient worsening of congestion", "HR, BP, daily weight"], ["Spironolactone (MRA)", "Aldosterone antagonism: anti-fibrotic, mild diuresis", "12.5 to 25 mg PO daily", "25 to 50 mg daily", "K >5.0 mEq/L, eGFR <30", "Hyperkalemia, gynecomastia (spironolactone), AKI", "K and creatinine at 3 to 7 days, then serially"], ["Dapagliflozin (SGLT2 inhibitor)", "Osmotic/natriuretic and metabolic effects independent of diabetes", "10 mg PO daily", "10 mg PO daily", "Type 1 diabetes / DKA risk; hold for procedures/illness", "Genital mycotic infection, volume depletion, euglycemic DKA", "Volume status, renal function"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the four HFrEF pillars: \"<strong>ABBS</strong>\" for <strong>A</strong>RNI (or ACEi/ARB), <strong>B</strong>eta-blocker, <strong>B</strong>lockade of aldosterone (MRA), and <strong>S</strong>GLT2 inhibitor. All four independently reduce mortality and should be started and uptitrated in parallel rather than one fully before the next, since low-dose all-four beats high-dose only-some."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not stack an ACE inhibitor with an ARNI: the overlapping bradykinin effect markedly raises angioedema risk, so a full 36-hour washout is mandatory when switching. And in the acutely decompensated, congested patient, do not initiate or uptitrate a beta-blocker until euvolemic, since its negative inotropy can deepen low-output failure."}]}, {"id": "advanced-fellow-concepts", "title": "Advanced: ventricular-arterial coupling", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The ventricle does not eject into a passive tube; it is dynamically coupled to the arterial system, and the efficiency of the whole pump depends on the match between the two. Ventricular-arterial coupling formalizes this as the ratio of arterial elastance to ventricular end-systolic elastance.", "depth": 2}, {"type": "defs", "entries": [{"term": "Ventricular elastance (Ees)", "def": "Slope of the ESPVR; a load-independent measure of contractility."}, {"term": "Arterial elastance (Ea)", "def": "An integrative index of arterial load, approximated by end-systolic pressure divided by stroke volume."}, {"term": "Coupling ratio (Ea/Ees)", "def": "Optimal mechanical efficiency near 0.5 to 1.0. A rising ratio (stiff arteries and/or weak ventricle) signals inefficient, decompensating coupling."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "In HFpEF, both Ees and Ea tend to rise (a stiff ventricle coupled to a stiff arterial tree), which is why these patients have such labile blood pressure: a small change in volume or vasomotor tone moves them a long way along a steep pressure-volume relationship, flipping between flash pulmonary edema and hypotension.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Coupling reframes vasodilator therapy. In a failing ventricle (low Ees) facing high arterial load (high Ea), reducing Ea with an afterload reducer moves the ratio back toward optimal and increases stroke work efficiency, delivering more forward output at less oxygen cost. This is the mechanistic heart of afterload reduction in HFrEF.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Open-access reviews of ventricular-arterial coupling, end-systolic and arterial elastance, and pressure-volume-loop derivation of contractility. Search \"ventricular-arterial coupling\" or \"end-systolic elastance\" on the landing page for full-text physiology reviews.", "url": "https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PMC: ventricular-arterial coupling reviews"}]}, {"id": "bedside-pearls", "title": "Bedside pearls: JVP and the splitting of S2", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Two physical findings turn the neck and the second heart sound into live hemodynamic monitors. Both are direct readouts of the physiology above, and both reward the fellow who can name every deflection."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>The jugular venous pulse</strong> is a window onto right atrial pressure. Its waveform has three ascents and two descents, each a specific right-heart event."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "The JVP waveform decoded.", "head": ["Deflection", "Event", "Abnormality"], "rows": [["a wave", "Atrial contraction", "Absent in atrial fibrillation; giant/cannon a in AV dissociation, complete heart block"], ["c wave", "Tricuspid bulging during RV isovolumic contraction", "Subtle; rarely used alone"], ["x descent", "Atrial relaxation, TV pulled down", "Prominent in cardiac tamponade"], ["v wave", "Atrial filling against a closed tricuspid valve", "Giant v wave in severe tricuspid regurgitation"], ["y descent", "Tricuspid opens, rapid RA emptying", "Steep in constrictive pericarditis; blunted/absent in tamponade"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Mnemonic for the JVP: the ascents spell \"<strong>a-c-v</strong>\" (<strong>a</strong>trial kick, <strong>c</strong>arotid/tricuspid bulge, <strong>v</strong>enous filling) with the x and y descents between them. Pair each with its lesion: absent a = atrial fibrillation, cannon a = AV dissociation, giant v = tricuspid regurgitation, steep y = constriction, blunted y = tamponade."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "Tamponade and constriction both raise venous pressure but split on the y descent: tamponade impairs all filling so the y descent is blunted (blunted x and y give a monophasic pulse), whereas constriction permits abrupt early filling then a sudden stop, giving a steep, prominent y descent. One waveform, two diagnoses."}, {"type": "p", "text": "<strong>The splitting of S2</strong> reports the timing of aortic (A2) versus pulmonic (P2) closure. Normally A2 precedes P2, and the gap widens on inspiration because increased venous return prolongs RV ejection (delaying P2) while pooling in the pulmonary bed shortens LV ejection (advancing A2). This is physiologic splitting."}, {"type": "table", "caption": "Patterns of S2 splitting.", "head": ["Pattern", "Finding", "Classic cause"], "rows": [["Physiologic", "Splits wider with inspiration, single on expiration", "Normal"], ["Wide (persistent)", "Split present throughout, widens with inspiration", "RBBB, pulmonic stenosis (delayed P2)"], ["Fixed", "Wide split that does not vary with respiration", "Atrial septal defect"], ["Paradoxical (reversed)", "Split on expiration, single on inspiration", "LBBB, severe aortic stenosis (delayed A2)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "text": "Fixed splitting in ASD arises because the left-to-right shunt equalizes the respiratory variation in filling between the two atria, so the inspiratory augmentation that normally delays P2 selectively is abolished. Paradoxical splitting flags a left-sided delay (LBBB, critical AS), which reverses the normal A2-before-P2 order so that inspiration brings the two sounds together instead of apart.", "depth": 3}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "For the electrocardiographic correlates of these anatomic territories and conduction abnormalities (inferior versus anterior STEMI patterns, RBBB and LBBB morphology, AV block), a curated labeled ECG library complements the anatomy above.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG library: territory and conduction patterns"}]}, {"id": "common-mistakes", "title": "Common mistakes", "body": [{"type": "list", "items": ["Treating ejection fraction as contractility. EF is load-dependent; it can look preserved in mitral regurgitation despite genuinely depressed contractile function (low Ees).", "Forgetting that inferior MI can involve the RV. RV infarction makes patients preload-dependent, so nitrates, diuretics, and morphine can crash the blood pressure; these patients often need fluids, not diuresis.", "Giving fluid to a decompensated HFrEF patient because the blood pressure is low. On a flat Starling curve the extra preload buys congestion, not output; the lever is usually afterload, not preload.", "Assuming coronary flow happens in systole. The left coronary bed fills in diastole, so tachycardia and low diastolic pressure are direct threats to myocardial supply.", "Calling every S2 split abnormal. Physiologic inspiratory splitting is normal; the alarms are fixed splitting (ASD) and paradoxical splitting (LBBB, severe AS).", "Ignoring wall stress when managing afterload. Laplace means a dilated ventricle at normal pressure is still under high wall stress; chamber size, not just blood pressure, drives oxygen demand.", "Starting or uptitrating a beta-blocker in a congested, decompensated HFrEF patient. Achieve euvolemia first; the negative inotropy can deepen low-output failure.", "Stacking an ACE inhibitor and ARNI, or an MRA on top of an unmonitored potassium. Respect the 36-hour ACEi-to-ARNI washout and recheck potassium and creatinine after any RAAS-blocker change.", "Reading a large a wave or absent a wave without checking the rhythm. Cannon a waves signal AV dissociation; a lost a wave signals atrial fibrillation. The neck often diagnoses the rhythm before the monitor."]}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 68-year-old with inferior ST-elevation MI (II, III, aVF) becomes profoundly hypotensive after a single sublingual nitroglycerin. Which mechanism best explains this response?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Nitrate-induced coronary steal from the LAD territory"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Right ventricular infarction has made cardiac output preload-dependent, and venodilation dropped RV filling"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Reflex tachycardia raised myocardial oxygen demand"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Acute mitral regurgitation from posteromedial papillary muscle rupture"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Nitrate-induced methemoglobinemia reducing oxygen delivery"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Inferior MI is RCA-territory in about 85 percent of cases, and the RCA supplies the right ventricle. RV infarction leaves output critically dependent on preload; nitrate venodilation abruptly reduces RV filling and forward output, precipitating hypotension. These patients typically need fluids, not preload reduction. Papillary muscle rupture is possible but presents with a new murmur and pulmonary edema over hours to days, not an immediate nitrate response."}, {"stem": "In a normal left ventricular pressure-volume loop, which corner corresponds to closure of the aortic valve and the second heart sound?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Bottom-right corner (end-diastole)"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Bottom-left corner (mitral opening)"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Top-left corner (end-systole, on the ESPVR)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Top-right corner (aortic opening)"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "The top-left corner of the loop is end-systole: the aortic valve closes (generating S2) at the point where LV pressure falls below aortic pressure, and this corner lies on the end-systolic pressure-volume relationship whose slope (Ees) indexes contractility. The bottom-right corner is end-diastole (mitral closure, S1)."}, {"stem": "Why does the subendocardium infarct before the subepicardium during a supply-demand mismatch?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "It has fewer mitochondria and lower metabolic reserve"}, {"key": "B", "text": "It is perfused last and compressed most by intramyocardial pressure during systole"}, {"key": "C", "text": "It receives blood only from collateral vessels"}, {"key": "D", "text": "It has a higher resting oxygen extraction than the epicardium"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Coronary perfusion of the left ventricle occurs mainly in diastole because systolic intramyocardial pressure compresses the vessels, and this compression is greatest in the subendocardium. The subendocardium therefore sits farthest along the perfusion gradient and is squeezed hardest, making it the first layer to become ischemic and infarct. Tachycardia (short diastole) and elevated LVEDP compound this."}, {"stem": "A wide, fixed splitting of S2 that does not vary with respiration is most characteristic of which condition?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Left bundle branch block"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Severe aortic stenosis"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Atrial septal defect"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Normal physiologic splitting"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "In an atrial septal defect the left-to-right shunt equalizes respiratory variation in atrial filling between the two sides, abolishing the selective inspiratory delay of P2 and producing a split that is wide and fixed across the respiratory cycle. LBBB and severe aortic stenosis delay A2 and cause paradoxical (reversed) splitting, which narrows with inspiration."}, {"stem": "A 61-year-old man with HFrEF (EF 28 percent) is euvolemic on lisinopril 20 mg daily, carvedilol 25 mg twice daily, and spironolactone 25 mg daily. His clinic BP is 118/72, HR 62, potassium 4.4, eGFR 68. To further reduce mortality, the best next step is to:", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Add sacubitril/valsartan the same day, continuing lisinopril for overlap"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Stop lisinopril, wait 36 hours, then start sacubitril/valsartan"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Add amlodipine for additional afterload reduction"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Add diltiazem to lower heart rate further"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Increase spironolactone to 50 mg twice daily"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Switching an ACE inhibitor to an ARNI is a mortality-reducing move in HFrEF, but the two must not overlap: combined ACE inhibition and neprilysin inhibition sharply increases angioedema risk, so a 36-hour washout is required. Dihydropyridine and especially non-dihydropyridine calcium blockers are not GDMT and diltiazem is contraindicated in HFrEF because of its negative inotropy. This patient is also missing an SGLT2 inhibitor, the fourth pillar, which would be the other high-value addition. Spironolactone is dosed once daily, not twice."}, {"stem": "A patient with stable angina remains symptomatic on maximally tolerated metoprolol and isosorbide mononitrate but has a resting heart rate of 52 and BP 104/64. Which add-on anti-anginal is most appropriate given these hemodynamics?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Diltiazem"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Additional long-acting nitrate around the clock"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Ranolazine"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Ivabradine titrated to a lower heart rate"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Ranolazine inhibits the late sodium current and reduces diastolic wall tension without lowering heart rate or blood pressure, making it the preferred add-on when a patient is already bradycardic and borderline hypotensive. Diltiazem would further lower heart rate and pressure; continuous nitrates cause tolerance and would drop pressure; ivabradine lowers heart rate further and is not indicated here. Ranolazine is anti-anginal only and does not substitute for prognosis-modifying therapy."}], "takeaways": ["Structure predicts pressure, pressure predicts flow, and flow predicts the exam and the drug: memorize the normal chamber pressures (RA 2-6, RV 25/4, PA 25/10, wedge 6-12, LV 120/8, aorta 120/80) as the anchors for every hemodynamic diagnosis.", "Stroke volume has exactly three levers (preload, afterload, contractility) plus heart rate; the normal ventricle is preload-sensitive and afterload-insensitive, and the failing ventricle inverts this, which is why afterload reduction is disease-modifying in HFrEF.", "Laplace's law (wall stress proportional to pressure times radius over twice thickness) unifies concentric versus eccentric hypertrophy and shows why a dilated heart is metabolically expensive.", "The pressure-volume loop reads out stroke volume (its width), stroke work (its area), preload and contractility (its corners), and specific valve lesions (missing isovolumic segments).", "The myocardium extracts ~70-75 percent of delivered oxygen at rest and is perfused in diastole, so ischemia is nearly always a flow problem worsened by tachycardia, hypotension, and elevated LVEDP; every anti-ischemic drug pulls a supply or demand lever, and the rate-pressure product tracks demand at the bedside.", "The four HFrEF pillars (ARNI/ACEi-ARB, beta-blocker, MRA, SGLT2 inhibitor) each independently reduce mortality and are started and uptitrated in parallel; respect the 36-hour ACEi-to-ARNI washout and monitor potassium and renal function.", "The JVP waveform and the splitting of S2 are live hemodynamic monitors: the y descent separates tamponade from constriction, and fixed versus paradoxical S2 splitting separates ASD from LBBB/severe AS."], "references": ["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology", "Klabunde RE. Cardiovascular Physiology Concepts", "Zipes DP, Libby P, Bonow RO, Mann DL, Tomaselli GF. Braunwald's Heart Disease: A Textbook of Cardiovascular Medicine", "Lilly LS. Pathophysiology of Heart Disease", "Heidenreich PA, et al. 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure", "Virani SS, et al. 2023 AHA/ACC/ACCP/ASPC/NLA/PCNA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Chronic Coronary Disease", "Humbert M, et al. 2022 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Pulmonary Hypertension", "Otto CM, et al. 2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease"]};
